#if(v_b2_ch5_scimitar != 0) {
 
"Flower! Illuna!" I say. "Could you go see why the two goblin mages haven't attacked us yet? You should be able to find where they're hiding, with a little help from Arraka."

"Oh, right, the goblins!" Flower says. "I completely forgot about them. I think I may have actually sensed one of them cast a spell when the orcs attacked us. Come on, Petal. It was this way!"

Not long after Flower and Illuna disappear into the woods, I decide that it's time to finally make my move.

I pull my scimitar out of its sheath, and I hurry towards one of the trees surrounding our area. I then use my weapon to cut the tree in a single movement, and just as the tree begins to fall to the ground, I sheathe my blade and I grab the tree with both my hands, in order to use it as my new weapon.

As I take a look towards the three orcs that were fighting Leila, all of the combatants from the battleground seem to have briefly stopped fighting, to look towards me, with shocked expressions on their faces. I take advantage of their momentary bewilderment to make a dash towards the three orcs with the maces, and I immediately crush one of them underneath the weight of the tree's trunk.

"Leila, step away from the orcs," I say.

 Leila complies right away, and she puts as much distance as she can between herself and the two remaining mace-wielding orcs, although one of them immediately begins to follow her. I swing my tree like a club, and I hit the orc that stayed behind from the side, completely crushing his internal organs, and killing him before he hits the ground. Seeing that there is only one orc left aside from the captain, Leila stops moving away from the battlefield, and she dashes straight for her pursuer, slicing his neck wide open, without giving him any time to react.
"HAHAHAHA!" Hadrik laughs, all of a sudden. "What a great idea! Why didn't I think of that?"

He then dashes towards a tree behind him and he pulls it straight out of the ground, roots and all. As soon as he acquires his new weapon, Hadrik tries to squash one of the ogres underneath its weight, but the monster simply blocks the tree with his club, as the force of the blow pushes him one foot into the ground. 

"Daren, you might want to move away from there..." I say, as Daren jumps away from the orc captain, and I swing my tree at him, in an attempt to squash him like I did with his companions.

 The orc does not let himself get intimidated, and he swings his flaming axes so fast that he cuts my tree into six pieces before it even reaches him. As the now burning pieces of wood fall on the ground beside him, the orc is looking straight at me, with a very pissed off look on his face.
"Damn..." I say, as I look at the big chunk of wood that I still have left in my hands.

Instead of engaging me, however, the orc captain reaches for a horn that he was wearing around his neck, and he blows in it as loud as he can. As soon as he does this, the ogres step back from Hadrik, and a very bright white light begins to engulf all of the monsters, while their bodies start to vibrate loudly.

}
