ID: B2-Ch08a-Energizer
TEXT: 

 "I didn't say that!"
"Well, what DID you say, then?" Melindra says.

"I was just-- ugh... are you even being serious, right now? Because with you, it's very hard to tell."

"Of course I'm being serious!" Melindra says. "Why wouldn't I be? It's not like I'm some maiden who was born yesterday. I know I may look nineteen years old, but I've been living for six hundred years. I've been with other men before. And it's not like I have any reason to not want to sleep with you, specifically. I don't particularly dislike you, we're both half-lessathi, and you are halfway decent looking. Well, slightly leaning towards the lower half, but still sort of half. You get what I mean."

"I can't tell if you are trying to compliment me, or if you're just insulting me right now..." I say.

"Look," Melindra says, "the bottom line is that there is nothing stopping us from having some fun for a few hours, and then calling it a day. There isn't even a need for me to drink the tea of infertility, because stillwaters are sterile and can't have children. And the silencing spell will still last for a good few hours, so it's not like anyone will be able to hear us. It's the perfect situation! Except for the small tent, that is... But nothing is perfect."

 "You know what?" I say. "You're right. I don't know what I was stressing about. Let's give it a shot!"
"That's more like it!" Melindra says. "Oh, but I hope you won't mind if I cast an energizing spell on you before we begin. It's just that I've had men run out of steam after only a few minutes before, and I wouldn't want to repeat the experience."

"Well, as long as the spell doesn't have any unwanted side effects..." I say.

"Oh, there's no need to worry about that!" Melindra says. "There are no side effects. That I know of. And besides, I will also be casting it on myself, so it's not like you will be the only one affected by it. Anyway, get ready, I'm casting the spell!"

As soon as Melindra is done casting the spell, I immediately start to feel the energy flowing all throughout my body. I feel as if I could run up and down a mountain, and then still have enough energy left to do a thousand push-ups. This spell is amazing! But it's very likely putting quite a strain on my body, so it probably wouldn't be wise to use it for too long. Well, a few hours won't kill me. Let's see how well this works.

choice("Continue", B2-Ch08a-Energizer2, v_current_scene = B2-Ch08a-Energizer2)


ID: B2-Ch08a-Energizer2
TEXT: 

 For the next several hours, Melindra and I both take full advantage of the energizing spell, and the more time passes, the more it seems like we could go on like this forever. I'm getting no signs of being tired, and even though we've had to switch positions half a dozen times due to the uncomfortable space we are in, neither of us seemed to want to end the night early.
When we are finally done for the night, the two of us get dressed, and I prepare to go to sleep for however many hours there are still left until morning.

"And here you were, saying that you didn't come to this tournament to have fun," Melindra says, with a smirk, as she ties her hair into a high ponytail.

"Okay, fine, I'll admit it," I say. "Maybe a little fun isn't so bad every once in a while."

"That's the spirit!" Melindra says, with a smile.

"Anyway, I think it's about time to go to bed," I say. "We've still got a few hours until morning, so we should try to make the most of them."

 "What are you talking about?" Melindra says, looking at me confused. "You're joking, right?... It's already morning. In fact, it's been morning for quite a while, now."
"What?" I ask her, in disbelief. "No, don't be silly! The sun isn't even up. I know that this tent is not very transparent, but we should still be able to see the rays of light when the sun rises, at least!"

"Well, then I guess that it must be really cloudy outside," Melindra says. "You don't need to take my word for it. Your stat device shows you the hour of the day, right? You can check it yourself. I'm telling you, it's been morning for at least two hours, if not more."

I suddenly panic, and I take my stat device out, to see what hour it is. Just as Melindra said, it seems that it's already well past sunrise. As I stare at my screen, I can see the hour clearly in front of my face, but it feels like my mind is still refusing to process the information.

"How did this happen?" I ask Melindra. "How is it morning already? I don't understand. It's only been a few hours!"

"Time flies when you're having fun," Melindra says. "Is this really the first time you've experienced an energizing spell? Don't worry, you'll get used to it, eventually. I had trouble like this too, the first time I cast the spell on myself, but now I don't have these sorts of problems anymore."

choice("Continue", B2-Ch08a-Energizer3, v_current_scene = B2-Ch08a-Energizer3)


ID: B2-Ch08a-Energizer3
TEXT: 

 "Why are you so calm about this?" I ask her. "I at least got an hour of sleep before you woke me up, but you didn't sleep at all! How are we going to handle ourselves after your energizing spell runs out?"
"We'll be fine!" Melindra says. "When we'll start to get tired, I'll just cast the energizing spell again, and it should hold us for the rest of the day."

"But aren't there supposed to be drawbacks if you cast these kinds of spells one after the other without a break?" I say.

"Eh..." Melindra says. "There might be some small risk of heart failure, but I'm sure we'll manage. We're both young. Well, you're sort of young, and I'm always young, but my point still stands. We shouldn't have anything to worry about."

"Okay, whatever," I say. "We'll see about that later. But for now, can you turn yourself invisible, so the others won't see you leaving the tent?"

 "Oh..." Melindra says. "Well, you see... while I may have learned that spell from Eiden, the thing is that I didn't really learn a complete version of it. The spell itself works just fine, but I can only cast it once a day, and I've already cast it once in the past twenty-four hours."
"Okay," I say. "Okay... No problem. We can fix this. I can't hear anyone outside, so I don't think they've woken up, yet. Flower had the last shift, if I remember correctly, so with a little luck, she might not see you when you walk out of here. Hold on, let me open the tent, and we'll see if the coast is clear."

"Wait!" Melindra shouts, when she sees me pull on the tent's zipper. "The silencing spell hasn't been canceled, yet!"

As I finish opening the tent, I immediately regret my decision, because every single one of my teammates are currently standing several dozen feet away from me, and they're all now staring straight at me and Melindra.

"Oh... right..." I say.

